{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4d325dff-fc11-4634-b4f5-93547e8c52ea","content":"There's no repository-specific documentation on this topic, so here's general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (cores go to `/cores` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **If `/cores` is empty**, macOS may have SIP restrictions. Check with:\n   ```bash\n   sysctl kern.coredump          # should be 1\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile     # shows path pattern\n   ```\n\n4. **Use macOS Crash Reports** — even without core dumps, macOS writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces and register state.\n\n5. **Attach lldb post-mortem** to the core file:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **If no core file exists**, reproduce the crash under lldb directly:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app\n   (lldb) run\n   # after crash:\n   (lldb) bt          # backtrace\n   (lldb) thread list\n   ```\n\n**Key note for NativeAOT**: Since there's no managed runtime, standard native debugging tools (`lldb`, core dumps) work directly — you don't need `dotnet-dump` or `createdump`. The crash reports and core files contain usable native stack traces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"84dd1e1d-f922-4f99-b941-f4a8d9321ac8","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"D7C6:100995:102E4E9:128968D:69F2B60E"},"id":"214af8bf-1b52-412d-8d6a-40e7a5052cb1","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:53:29.383Z","parentId":"577d0969-6394-4406-ba8f-42de6919f0ca"}
